  <file id="938" original="/csunplugged/topics/content/en/error-detection-and-correction/programming-challenges/detect-parity-error-in-any-rows-after-input/scratch-hints.md" source-language="en" target-language="en-UD" datatype="plaintext">
    <body>
      <trans-unit id="10403" identifier="21ce6d71c6e12f134d63249aee4266a2">
        <source>For this challenge you need to use a list to store all the rows (each
item in the list is a row).</source>
        <target>crwdns10403:0crwdne10403:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10404" identifier="8400a7a88dcd3b9e1e93283c0dd092ca">
        <source>You then need to go through each row (item of your list) and check if
they have a parity error (i.e. the total number of black cards in
each row is odd).</source>
        <target>crwdns10404:0crwdne10404:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10405" identifier="558ae28c5130e7a1e33b56250e0c8b5b">
        <source>If one or more rows have parity errors, you then need to find their
positions in the list and report these positions as the output.</source>
        <target>crwdns10405:0crwdne10405:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10406" identifier="39a3d6ec587f37416481bfa2bde8e014">
        <source>To make a new list select “Make a list” under “Data” script.</source>
        <target>crwdns10406:0crwdne10406:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[2]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10407" identifier="db9e820b03f12bab15f9a6d93f82f07e">
        <source>Add items to your list by using the &lt;code&gt;scratch:add () to [rows v]&lt;/code&gt; block.</source>
        <target>crwdns10407:0crwdne10407:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[3]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10408" identifier="56551f776a8a9db0882066a2e1413f68">
        <source>You can access an item in a specific position in your list by using the
&lt;code&gt;scratch:item () of [rows v] :: list&lt;/code&gt; block.</source>
        <target>crwdns10408:0crwdne10408:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[4]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10409" identifier="6c4eda1e9828b61597f0743ec817ad5e">
        <source>The &lt;code&gt;scratch:length of [rows v] :: list&lt;/code&gt; block reports how many items are
in the list.</source>
        <target>crwdns10409:0crwdne10409:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[5]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10410" identifier="1e5f887e084cc57af7b327361e670030">
        <source>You need to delete all the previous items from your list at the start of
your program.</source>
        <target>crwdns10410:0crwdne10410:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[6]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10411" identifier="baea0edf25cabd81ebd6bef7e52fb9d6">
        <source>If you don’t do this, your new items get added to the list every time you
run your program.</source>
        <target>crwdns10411:0crwdne10411:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[6]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10412" identifier="952eb555493b8c87176765333cb12658">
        <source>To delete all the items from your list select “all” from the drop down
list on the &lt;code&gt;scratch:delete (all v) of [rows v]&lt;/code&gt; block.</source>
        <target>crwdns10412:0crwdne10412:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[6]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10413" identifier="de3531d0c13aeef433d4ba91577c0a29">
        <source>You can access a letter at the specified position in a string by using
the &lt;code&gt;scratch:letter (1) of [world]&lt;/code&gt; block under “Operators”.</source>
        <target>crwdns10413:0[world]crwdne10413:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[7]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10414" identifier="82f1af887eb4c2c1bc3483004bed0cc0">
        <source>For example: &lt;code&gt;scratch:letter (1) of [world] //w&lt;/code&gt;</source>
        <target>crwdns10414:0[world]crwdne10414:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[7]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10415" identifier="72c12b6a729819466dd76b1ecc58684d">
        <source>In this challenge you need to access all the letters in user’s input
(each row of the parity trick) and check to see how many of them
are equal to B (black).</source>
        <target>crwdns10415:0crwdne10415:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[8]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10416" identifier="1f12f28ec0f212cc1c82264b8baef08b">
        <source>Store the total number of black squares in a variable called
“black cards total”.</source>
        <target>crwdns10416:0crwdne10416:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[8]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10417" identifier="17316ceafe6f34cd99cfed49b8f3ef17">
        <source>You can find how many letters a string has by using the
&lt;code&gt;scratch:length of [world]&lt;/code&gt; block unders “Operators”.</source>
        <target>crwdns10417:0[world]crwdne10417:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /ul/li[9]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10418" identifier="87d4fd226e757d4f0e6d9bbbf1ba7c79">
        <source>To find out if a number is even or odd, use the &lt;code&gt;scratch:() mod ()&lt;/code&gt; block
(under &quot;Operators&quot;) to find the remainder after dividing that number by
two.</source>
        <target>crwdns10418:0crwdne10418:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[10]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10419" identifier="2e95a7ff37597c9b5e8d5515f0807395">
        <source>If the remainder is zero the number is even.</source>
        <target>crwdns10419:0crwdne10419:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[10]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10420" identifier="630f2e24931e9ee5a45ae35bea13d555">
        <source>For example: &lt;code&gt;scratch:(37) mod (10) //7&lt;/code&gt;</source>
        <target>crwdns10420:0crwdne10420:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[10]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
    </body>
